--------
[1] USA (Travel alert)
Date: Fri 13 Jul 2012
Source: WKYC-TV [edited]
http://www.wkyc.com/news/health/article/252155/7/Olympics-brings-worries-of-measles-outbreak

Olympics brings worries of measles outbreak
--------------------------------------
It's a disease that was technically eradicated in this country [USA] twelve years ago, but unvaccinated international travelers and those who are not protected here, run the risk of measles especially after the Olympics. While the Olympics bring the world together, the competition can also provide a breeding ground for infectious disease like measles. The issue, travelers who are not adequately protected bringing back the illness.

The CDC reported 17 measles outbreaks in 2011, four times the average. There were 222 cases, most linked to international travel, none were in Ohio.

The London Olympics are a huge concern. The UK and other parts of the world are dealing with widespread cases. If you enter a room with an infected person and you're not vaccinated, you have a 90-95 percent chance of getting measles. Now, multiply that by a worldwide event bringing in hundreds of thousands. Measles spreads like the common cold. A cough could infect surfaces and even the air. When symptoms appear, they usually come with a rash, fever, cough and or conjunctivitis. Measles can cause pneumonia and in the worst cases brain swelling and death...

The CDC recommends children get two doses of the MMR (measles, mumps, and rubella) vaccine. The first at 12-15 months, the next at 4 to 6 years. If you're not absolutely sure you've had those doses, the CDC says get another one before you travel.

---
